President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring May 2015 as Older Americans Month. The proclamation recognizes the contributions and sacrifices made by older Americans and emphasizes the importance of ensuring their care, support, and respect. The proclamation also highlights the changing demographic landscape of the United States, with the population of older Americans expected to increase significantly in the coming years. President Obama mentions the upcoming 2015 White House Conference on Aging, which aims to address the changing landscape of aging and advance policies that support older Americans. The proclamation also acknowledges the anniversaries of Medicare, Medicaid, the Older Americans Act, and Social Security, and reaffirms the President's commitment to strengthening these programs. Finally, President Obama calls upon all Americans to acknowledge the contributions of older Americans during the month of May and throughout the year.